5.5 SCALING UP TO GPT-3 175B

As a Ô¨Ånal stress test for LoRA, we scale up to GPT-3 with 175 billion parameters. Due to the high training cost, we only report the typical standard deviation for a given task over random seeds, as opposed to providing one for every entry. See Section D.4 for details on the hyperparameters used.

As shown in Table 4, LoRA matches or exceeds the Ô¨Åne-tuning baseline on all three datasets. Note that not all methods beneÔ¨Åt monotonically from having more trainable parameters, as shown in Figure 2. We observe a signiÔ¨Åcant performance drop when we use more than 256 special tokens for preÔ¨Åx-embedding tuning or more than 32 special tokens for preÔ¨Åx-layer tuning. This corroborates similar observations in Li & Liang (2021). While a thorough investigation into this phenomenon is out-of-scope for this work, we suspect that having more special tokens causes the input distribution to shift further away from the pre-training data distribution. Separately, we investigate the performance of different adaptation approaches in the low-data regime in Section F.3.

